<TEXT>
democrats and republicans narrowed differences 
sunday over new taxes on the rich gasoline levies and medicare 
cuts even as bush administration officials angrily stalked out of 
deficitreduction talks 
congressional leaders of both parties negotiated until about 
1130 pm sunday over a 250 billion package of tax increases and 
spending cuts in agriculture student loans and dozens of other 
programs they said they would resume talking monday 
weve made good progress in many areas said senate majority 
leader george mitchell dmaine but he conceded the remaining 
areas of disagreement are important ones 
weekend bargaining saw the two sides move toward each other in 
several areas including the question of how and how high to 
raise taxes on the rich 
the talks proceeded on the eve of what lawmakers hoped would be 
congress last week before adjournment for the year in the scant 
time left house and senate leaders say they would still like to 
tackle bills dealing with civil rights air pollution and child 
care 
budget negotiators seemed willing to raise the incometax rate 
on the wealthy to 31 percent up from its current 28 percent they 
were also close on proposals to limit the deductions the wealthiest 
taxpayers could claim 
but democrats were insisting on a 75 percent surtax on incomes 
exceeding 1 million annually the proposal if adopted would 
allow democrats to claim that rates on millionaires were raised 
substantially 
we think its good public policy and fair said mitchell 
republicans were adamantly against that idea and instead wanted 
higher limitations on millionaires deductions 
white house chief of staff john sununu accused democrats of 
being too divided to respond to the latest gop offer 
were not going to negotiate with democrats who cant come to 
an agreement among themselves he said as he left the capitol 
with white house budget chief richard darman and treasury secretary 
nicholas brady this was a great offer 
but mitchell denied that saying i can say to you democrats 
are unified 
despite the standoff over taxes the two sides moved closer in 
other areas said a democratic congressional official who asked to 
not be identified 
democrats offered to raise the gasoline tax 5 cents above its 
current 9centagallon level republicans were seeking a 7cent 
increase 
democrats were offering to reduce medicare by as much as 44 
billion 3 billion less than republicans were demanding 
in addition democrats were seeking to boost the 51300 wage 
cap from which medicare taxes are deducted to 125000 republicans 
want to increase the cap to 98000 the 145 percent medicare tax 
is part of the social security deduction 
republicans have been fearful of late that democrats have made 
the taxtherich battle cry their own barely two weeks from 
election day earlier in the day white house aides said higher 
levies on the rich were on the way 
this is one of the alltime false issues the richpoor 
thing said administration budget director richard darman this 
compromise in the end will tax the rich 
working against a wednesday deadline when stopgap spending 
authority expires bargainers were trying to find middle ground 
between separate deficitreduction plans approved by the house and 
senate last week the senate bill preferred by bush had more 
moderate tax increases on the wealthy took a bigger bite out of 
medicare spending and doubled the gasoline tax 
we feel very strongly there should be a surcharge and a rate 
increase on higherincome levels house speaker thomas foley 
dwash told reporters 
its got to move in the direction of being fairer in terms of 
taxes in other words asking the wealthiest americans to pay their 
fair share said house majority leader richard gephardt dmo 
who like darman appeared on abctvs this week with david 
brinkley program 
darman said bush would accept a 31 percent rate on the rich up 
from 28 percent if the rate on those slightly less welloff was 
reduced from 33 percent to 31 percent that tradeoff eliminating 
the socalled bubble would increase taxes for 700000 people and 
reduce them for 5 million others while raising an estimated 7 
billion in additional revenue 
but mitchell said democrats would not accept that offer alone 
it obviously would have to be accompanied by other measures 
so people whose taxes were cut would be required to pay something 
to offset that reduction mitchell said on nbctvs meet the 
press program 
were not hung up on any one formula but rather the principle 
of fairness mitchell added 
the senate approved a bipartisan budget friday shrinking the 
growth of medicare by 49 billion over the next five years 
including 17 billion to be directed at the elderly and handicapped 
served by the program 
the house plan which attracted only 10 gop votes limited those 
cuts to 43 billion of which participants would bear 10 billion 
in reduced benefits and higher costs 
the house would leave the 9centagallon gasoline tax alone 
while the senate would raise it gradually to 185 cents 
democrats have conceded that the final compromise is likely to 
include some increase in the gasoline levy they also have said 
another feature of the house bill likely will be dropped a 
oneyear delay in inflation adjustments on incometax brackets and 
the personal exemption which would have caused slight increases in 
the tax bills of everyone who pays income tax 
virtually certain to emerge in the final product are several 
other features the two bills had in common including higher taxes 
on alcohol tobacco airline tickets and luxury items such as 
yachts and jewelry 
spending cuts would be administered to agriculture student loan 
and veterans programs 
the deficitreduction bill combined with other savings mainly 
defense cuts and reduced interest payments on the debt would 
lower the deficit by 40 billion for the fiscal year that began 
oct 1 and 460 billion more over the next five years 
the budget stalemate cost the government 16 million when 
agencies shut down over the columbus day weekend earlier in 
october the general accounting office said in a report 
the government had closed because in an effort to keep pressure 
on budget writers bush vetoed emergency spending legislation after 
federal authority to spend money had elapsed 
</TEXT>
