<TEXT>
on the face of it the united states government 
and environmentalists may seem an unlikely alliance but allied 
they are in their opposition to the resumption of commercial 
whaling in iceland in the second of two stories ap science editor 
paul raeburn examines the efforts to blunt icelands contentions 
that its whales are not endangered 
 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
a whale is the most beautiful animal 
i have ever seen the poet wh auden wrote during a visit to 
iceland in 1936 to see it torn to pieces with steam winches and 
cranes is enough to make one a vegetarian for life 
that kind of revulsion has helped make the global 
savethewhales campaign one of the most dramatic successes of the 
environmental movement an international moratorium on commercial 
whaling was instituted in 1986 and environmentalists now are 
pushing for a permanent ban on all whaling 
we would certainly be against whaling until we could 
definitely show it would not affect the whale stocks says 
kevin chu if there is any doubt we want to err on the side of 
conservation 
thats tough talk and it doesnt come from an 
environmentalist chu is a foreign affairs officer in the us 
state departments bureau of oceans and international environmental 
and scientific affairs 
asked to describe the us position on whaling chu says the 
united states is against it 
the perhaps unusual consensus among the government and 
environmental groups is fueled by two things concern that whales 
are in danger of extinction and the kind of sentiments evoked by 
auden 
the government takes a strong antiwhaling stance because the 
only voices we hear are the voices of the environmentalists chu 
said 
iceland one of the three major whaling nations along with 
norway and japan argues strenuously that the whales it wants to 
hunt are not endangered and that it should be allowed to resume 
commercial whaling 
but even if scientists eventually agree the populations are 
indeed not endangered the campaign to save the whales is unlikely 
to die 
politically it comes down to a relatively simple thing 
said william evans the us representative to the international 
whaling commission there are a number of countries and 
scientists that believe there is not a justification or 
need for any country to continue to harvest these animals 
im completely of the mindset that we have to protect oceans 
for our own survival and the whales are a component of this 
ecosystem said sally shoup of greenpeace we have to stop this 
devastation of the other creatures on the planet if we want to 
protect ourselves 
i think whales are special she said i think they are 
intelligent creatures i think icelanders can understand that as 
well 
the savethewhales campaign began in 1972 when the landmark 
un conference on the environment in a 530 vote passed a 
resolution calling for a 10year moratorium on whaling whalers 
killed 46000 whales that year 
the united states immediately proposed the moratorium to the 
whaling commission which rejected it but the us continued to 
push in 1982 the commission finally approved a moratorium 
beginning in 1986 
what we were going to do was take five years of no whaling 
said evans the us representative to the commission well we 
havent had five years of no whaling because iceland invented 
scientific whaling 
a clause in the international whaling convention allows the 
killing of whales for scientific purposes iceland exploited it 
you have the same boats and the same people and you take the 
same whales and you sell it to the same people and you call it 
scientific whaling said roger payne a noted whale expert and 
president of the long term research institute in lincoln mass 
its a joke 
johann sigurjonsson senior whale specialist at icelands marine 
research institute vigorously disagreed those who have been 
following what were doing understand the seriousness of what were 
doing he said 
in 1985 the last year of its commercial whaling operation 
iceland killed 344 whales it caught 116 in 1986 and the number 
declined to 68 in 1989 this year iceland shut down its whaling 
operation entirely but it continues to press vigorously for a 
resumption of commercial killing of fin sei and minke whales 
congress has passed several laws that allow the united states to 
impose economic sanctions against countries that violate whaling 
commission regulations 
icelands critics have argued that the scientific whaling is 
merely commercial whaling under another name and have pressed the 
united states to impose sanctions the united states might be 
reluctant to do so however because iceland is the site of a 
strategic nato base 
payne said the methods used to estimate whale populations are 
highly imprecise and that the icelandic scientific research has 
shown us nothing we didnt know before 
it could take as long as 100 years to know how many whales can 
be captured without reducing the size of a given whale population 
he said 
the international whaling commission has stopped releasing 
estimates of whale populations as it undertakes new assessments 
because it fears its previous estimates could be wildly inaccurate 
said martin harvey the commissions executive officer 
the old estimates suggest that since the advent of whaling the 
population of fin whales has been reduced from 548000 to 120000 
while sei whales declined from 256000 to 54000 
the commission completed its assessment of minke whales this 
year and concluded that about 28000 are in icelandic waters 
which we think is not too far from the number there ever was 
said ray gambell a whale biologist and the commissions secretary 
some 600000 minke whales live in antarctic waters 
sigurjonsson calls the debate over population numbers a stalling 
tactic 
you can set catch limits very cautiously he said but to 
reject any catch because you dont know the exact figure thats a 
difficult question and it may take you years to find out the exact 
number 
part of the problem were having with iceland is what is a 
reasonable doubt said chu of the state department 
the scientific committee of the whaling commission did say a 
take of 200 minkes would probably not harm the stock chu said 
it was the probably that first catches ones attention were 
simply not prepared to let the moratorium lapse at this point 
even if the moratorium was lifted or modified iceland couldnt 
resume commercial whaling until at least 1992 gambell said the 
commission cant decide until may at the earliest to allow 
iceland to proceed and any such decision would not take effect 
until 90 days later too late for the 1991 season 
chu said one alternative might be for the whaling commission to 
allow iceland to resume hunting whales up to a quota rather than 
have iceland withdraw from the commission as it has threatened to 
do if iceland withdrew it no longer would be bound by the 
moratorium 
im afraid the conservation of whales will suffer if we take 
too strong a stand said chu who said he was expressing his 
personal views not those of the state department on the other 
hand i think the united states is not in a position to allow them 
some sort of a quota it would be extremely difficult to bend the 
moratorium 
icelands whalers also may be facing problems on a new front 
at home 
the opinion of the icelandic public is changing said 
gudmundur hermansson who covers whaling for morgunbladid 
icelands largest daily newspaper 
in 1986 probably 80 percent to 90 percent of the public 
supported the government hermansson said but that figure is 
dropping he said 
opinion polls show clearly this support was getting less and 
less every year hermansson said i dont think whaling will be 
taken up again 
</TEXT>
