<TEXT>
burmas rebellious buddhist monks their 
monasteries ringed by troops appeared sunday to have given in to 
an ultimatum by the countrys authoritarian rulers to end their 
boycott of the military 
reports reaching the burmese capital from mandalay the center 
of the defiance campaign said the monks would end their refusal to 
minister to soldiers in a formal announcement later sunday 
armed troops cordoned off buddhist monasteries in the central 
burma city saturday after the military government said it would 
dissolve monks groups involved in the boycott 
a state radio announcement repeated throughout the day saturday 
interspersed with martial music said illegal monks 
organizations had been participating in politics against the rules 
of buddhism 
such illegal organizations will be dissolved from 
midnight tonight and members of such illegal organizations are 
not eligible to be members of the sangha rangoon radio said the 
sangha is the main religious governing body in predominately 
buddhist burma 
at least six major mandalay monasteries were surrounded by 
troops and police and closed their gates 
but witnesses contacted by telephone said the gates were opened 
and monks came out on their morning alms rounds sunday without 
interference from the troops monks traditionally receive offerings 
of food from the faithful in the early morning 
it was not clear whether action would be taken against the 
monks who began their boycott after troops put down an 
antigovernment demonstration in mandalay last august the boycott 
spread to other areas including rangoon located 350 miles south 
of mandalay 
western observers in rangoon said the monks refusal to minister 
to the soldiers was the equivalent of excommunication 
the government said such organizations have jeopardized the 
peace and stability of the country and threatened the breakup of 
the central sangha organization by various means including 
threats blackmail and boycott 
a western observer in rangoon said any move against members of 
the sangha is bound to cause some kind of popular reaction he 
spoke by telephone and on condition of anonymity like other 
observers who commented on the situation 
about 85 percent of burmas 40 million people are buddhist and 
some 300000 monks live in monasteries around the country in 
buddhist societies monks are regarded as spiritual leaders of the 
community and also play a key role in popular celebrations and 
various rites 
another burma expert said the government is challenging burmas 
religious soul and going against traditions that revere the monks 
its going to be very difficult for the soldiers to fire on 
the monks if ordered to shoot it will really bring into question 
how reliant the soldiers are said josef silverstein a us 
political scientist in new jersey 
if they shoot defenseless monks who are only withholding 
religious services as a moral weapon there could be enormous 
street protests this is morality vs weapons whats left for 
people whose vote has been rejected by the military 
the groups singled out by the government included the young 
monks organization in mandalay on sept 6 the organization 
announced a boycott of religious ceremonies for soldiers and their 
families after troops broke up an antigovernment protest in the 
city a month earlier 
during the aug 8 demonstration troops killed four people 
including two monks according to western diplomats in rangoon 
from mandalay in central burma the monks boycott spread west 
to the district of monya and to some monasteries in the capital 
rangoon 350 miles south of mandalay 
monks emerged at the head of antigovernment protests during the 
1988 prodemocracy uprising in which the army killed thousands of 
people 
a western source said about 160 monasteries in the capital have 
taken up the protest involving about 15000 monks a quarter of 
those in the city however it appeared the boycott was most 
widespread in mandalay where there are about 20000 monks he 
said 
mandalay was a major center of unrest during the 1988 uprising 
and monks took over the city administration for several weeks 
the military government held a national election may 27 that was 
easily won by the national league for democracy the main 
opposition group but the government has refused to hand over power 
and has arrested the main opposition leaders 
