<DOCNO> AP901021-0021 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
war and rumors of war are bad for 
business at the suez canal 
when politics get sticky revenues go down in the waning weeks 
of 1990 politics are sticky indeed 
when the world is happy the suez canal is happy when things 
go wrong somewhere else they go bad here said capt adel abdel 
salam the canals chief pilot 
oil the black gold of the middle east has been the savior and 
bankroll of the suez canal since the late 1940s 
as the strategic connection between western oil consumers and 
middle eastern oil producers the canal felt an immediate impact 
when iraq seized kuwait on aug 2 
warships steaming to and from the persian gulf keep the waterway 
busy but they dont pay much money tankers ferrying oil to europe 
pay a lot but fewer are coming through 
egypt debtridden and deeply involved in the gulf crisis 
desperately needs the dollars the canal should be providing 
its most lucrative revenue source is the paychecks sent home by 
egyptians abroad that is dwindling with the return of about 
350000 workers from the gulf many of them penniless 
the assassination of a leading egyptian politician oct 12 in 
downtown cairo devastated an already reeling tourist industry 
until aug 2 tourism was egypts secondbest source of money 
for ordinary egyptians a problem at the suez canal is a 
personal misfortune they view it as a monument to national pride 
much as ancient egyptians viewed the pyramids and sphinx 
we dug the canal with our lives our skulls our bones our 
blood president gamal abdel nasser said in announcing on july 
26 1956 that egypt was taking the canal from a britishfrench 
concession 
the united states had little interest in the canal until its 
troops found themselves defending north africa in world war ii 
afterward a burgeoning consumer society demanded more oil ores 
and rubber from the east and they came cheaper via suez 
trouble never has been far from the 101milelong ditch linking 
the mediterranean and red seas via egypts bitter lakes and the 
gulf of suez 
as many as 20000 laborers are thought to have died digging the 
canal which was inaugurated in 1869 in an orgy of opulence that 
nearly bankrupted the country 
during the 20th century suez often has been at or near the 
center of conflict 
russian warships passed through it in 1905 en route to 
catastrophic defeat by the japanese off korea in world war i 
german uboats tried to sever england from its colonies east of 
suez by keeping cargo ships from using the canal 
in 1939 italian dictator benito mussolini used it as a pathway 
to conquer ethiopia 
field marshal erwin rommel germanys world war ii military 
genius was unable to capture the canal and the persian oil fields 
beyond germany bombed it 64 times stopping traffic for 76 days 
ships sunk during egypts 1967 war with israel blocked all 
traffic for eight years 
canal business soured during the 1980s because of the iraqiran 
wqar in which hundreds of oil tankers were attacked in the persian 
gulf 
for egypt which owns the canal iraqs invasion of kuwait was 
far more than a problem between arab brothers 
both countries were good customers of suez each year shipping 
seven million tons of oil westward the un embargo ended that 
oil that would have passed through the canal to europe is being 
consumed east of suez by forces sent to confront iraq 
through august the canals monthly tanker tonnage averaged more 
than 135 million tons in september the first full month under 
embargo the tonnage was 11 million 
war makes civilization go faster but on the suez canal 
things slow down said abdel salam the chief pilot its not 
devastating but yes were suffering 
how much became evident in september ezzat adel chairman of 
the suez canal authority said the gulf trouble ould cost 400 
million in the fiscal year that started a month before the 
invasion in 1989 canal revenues brought the government nearly 
14 billion 
the crisis brings into focus two persistent irritants for the 
canal authority neutrality and nuclear ships 
under the 1888 constantinople convention the suez canal must 
accept all ships but egypt interprets one clause as allowing it to 
deny access to those likely to endanger egypts security 
that was the basis of a ban on ships flying israels flag until 
1979 when egypt signed a peace treaty with the jewish state and 
on vessels either carrying nuclear weapons or powered by nuclear 
energy 
iraqi ships now use the canal despite egypts strong antiiraq 
position in the gulf crisis if war began egypt probably would ban 
them 
the nuclear ban is so politically sensitive that nobody will 
talk about it 
in august as the united states built up its forces to face 
iraq the nuclearpowered aircraft carrier dwight d eisenhower 
passed through the canal to the red sea then returned two weeks 
later 
egypt did not ask about the carriers propulsion system 
</TEXT>
