malaysia has been ruled by a multiracial coalition based on 
parties made up of different ethnic and racial groups since 
independence in 1957 
malays comprise about 53 percent of the population of 178 
million chinese make up about 32 percent with indians and other 
races making up the balance 
the national front includes the malaysian chinese association 
malaysian indian congress and seven smaller parties 
malaysia has had seven previous elections since independence 
but in those votes the fragmented opposition made little headway 
against the national front establishing only regional bases of 
power 
in the weekend vote however the electorate for the first time 
had an organized alternative representing the same ethnic mosaic as 
the national front 
but the campaign was largely devoid of issues focusing instead 
on personality attacks 
the opposition charged the national front with economic 
mismanagement corruption indifference to ethnic tensions and 
erosion of judicial powers none of these allegations made much 
impact the opposition also promised sweeping tax cuts 
mahathir claims credit for one of the fastest growing economies 
