<TEXT>
officials from 13 southern states and puerto 
rico on sunday labeled their region the least educated in the 
nation and announced formation of the southern literacy forum to 
combat the problem 
there are thousands of individual literacy programs out there 
a lot of good is going on but its like dipping the mississippi 
river dry with a teaspoon former mississippi gov william f 
winter wrote in a report released at a news conference 
a center will help us coordinate on a regional basis what 
has to be one of the most important projects that anybody can be 
involved in he wrote 
in the 13 southern states at least 30 percent of adults are 
high school dropouts this is true in only three of the other 37 
states the report said 
the forum will be an offshoot of the southern growth policies 
board which southern governors created to develop their economies 
and people the agency is based in research triangle park nc 
the board received the report sunday from its chairman 
louisiana gov buddy roemer who also announced creation of the 
forum 
also attending the boards 18th annual meeting were north 
carolina gov james martin and officials from alabama arkansas 
florida georgia kentucky mississippi oklahoma south carolina 
tennessee virginia west virginia and puerto rico 
literacy would improve the quality of our work force lower 
the unempooyment rates and make our citizenry have a higher 
selfesteem roemer said it will be helpful to join with our 
neighbors and put together a plan to develop literacy opportunities 
for the region 
what the forum does is show which ideas are best and promote 
them martin said its sort of like blocking and tackling 
weve got to deal with the fundamentals 
the report literacy is everybodys business noted the very 
meaning of literacy has changed throughout the century 
todays literacy would seem like higher education to our 
grandparents it said in fact the education that was once 
sufficient to enable any ambitious adult to get ahead now cant 
even help him hold his place on the assembly line 
during world war ii a worker able to read at a 4thgrade level 
could manage entrylevel jobs an 8thgrade education was enough to 
get by in the mid1960s 
today even entrylevel jobs may require some college education 
and farming a crucial part of the southern economy needs more 
than a field hands skills 
once it was enough to read the ripeness of a tomato or the 
skys forecast of rain todays farmer is the chief executive 
officer purchasing agent personnel officer and financial manager 
of a rapidly evolving highly sophisticated business the report 
said 
at the same time he must be a scientist to select his seed or 
stock plants a computer operator to disburse the proper fertilizer 
to his fields or feedstuffs to his livestock a production expert 
to manage the harvest and a marketing whiz to sell his 
commodity it said 
the report estimated that literacy programs currently are 
attended by fewer than 10 percent of southern adults who need to 
improve their reading speaking and mathematics skills 
a regional partnership is needed to expand such offerings 
because no single southern state has the money or other resources 
to reach and teach all the people who need help the report said 
the southern literacy forum will help states put together such 
programs pay for or conduct research to improve them and provide 
information training and other help to local literacy programs 
the policies board has a 12 million budget 31 percent of it 
from state dues and appropriations and the rest from grants 
associate memberships and publications 
initial support for the organization will come from 175000 the 
board hopes to raise from foundations and private donors 
