<TEXT>
the colombian government plans to 
increase incentives for petroleum and gas exploration by foreign 
companies president cesar gaviria said 
the government will begin a rapid evaluation of the changes 
necessary to make exploration of inactive areas more 
attractive gaviria said saturday while inaugurating a new gas 
pipeline in central colombia 
gaviria did not specify what types of changes the government was 
considering the presidents comments were reported sunday by local 
news media 
current government contracts assign oil exploration to several 
multinational companies operating in colombia if petroleum 
deposites are discovered the government and the foreign companies 
share the cost of developing them 
colombia receives 60 percent of the petroleum produced while the 
foreign companies take the remaining 40 percent and pay taxes on 
their earnings 
the companies are pushing for a better deal because of the high 
risks involved in searching for petroleum in colombia 
one of the countrys leftist guerrilla groups the national 
liberation army or eln has repeatedly sabotaged oil facilities 
and kidnapped employees of foreign petroleum companies 
gaviria said saturday that the rebels should abandon the 
campaign and participae in next years assembly to rewrite 
colombias constitution and reform its democracy 
attacks by the rebels on petroleum facilities have caused 520 
million in losses and have produced a steep drop in exploration 
activity according to the state oil company ecopetrol 
of the 450000 barrels of oil produced each day in colombia 
220000 barrels are exported petroleum colombias leading export 
is expected to earn it more than 15 billion dollars in foreign 
exchange this year 
